DETAILED NARRATIVE
 POST-CRASH INSPECTION REPORT #23-24-000015
Commercial Vehicle Enforcement Division

                                                                   

                                                 

 
                                                   

A.    CRASH SUMMARY:

On April 10, 2023, at 1300 hours, I, TFC Duane Rust #6313, assigned to the Upper Marlboro Weight and Inspection Facility, was contacted by Sgt. Gregory Hentnick to respond to the area of S/B Route 4 (Pennsylvania Ave) near Ritchie-Marlboro Road for a report of a collision involving a commercial vehicle. I arrived on the scene at approximately 1333 hours.  The Forestville barrack investigating trooper, Trooper Christopher Reid, and Sgt. Kevin Zarzecki of the MSP Crash Team had arrived prior to my arrival and were interviewing witnesses. I learned that the occupants of the commercial vehicle were transported to area hospitals prior to my arrival and had not yet been identified.

The collision occurred on a strait portion of southbound Route 4 (Pennsylvania Ave). The roadway surface was level and free of debris. The weather was clear and the visibility was daylight unrestricted. The scene consisted of the following. A white Ford E350 cargo van was resting on the driver's side and had collided with a large tree off the right side of the roadway. The impact caused the passenger seat area of the van to be completely crushed and wrapped around the tree. Fire and EMS personnel were working to extricate the driver of the van for approximately an hour.  The driver was transported to the University of Maryland R. Adams Cowley Shock Trauma Center by aviation after he was extricated. The dark-blue International two-axle dump truck owned by Flippo Construction Co Inc (USDOT# 235198) had come to final rest in the wooded area off the right side of the roadway. The CMV had sustained catastrophic damage as a result of the collision. Vehicle parts and debris were spread around the CMV.  The truck was resting on the driver's side and the dump bed was hyperextended beyond normal operating range. The dump bed had separated from the hydraulic lift cylinder. Rescue personnel had cut the roof off of the CMV to extricate the occupants prior to my arrival. The batteries and fuel tank had been flung from the CMV during the collision sequence.  I contacted Lorraine at Flippo Construction and obtained the driver and passenger identities and relayed them to the College Park Barrack emergency dispatcher. 

After the scene was processed by Sgt. Zarzecki and the vehicle was returned to the roadway by Central Towing, A North American Standard Level I Inspection was conducted in the roadway on Route 4. All lighting devices were inoperative since the batteries were thrown from the CMV. Air was supplied to the CMV by the tow company to measure the brakes. Following the inspection, Central Towing towed the CMV to their tow lot. 

Sgt. Zarzecki will be submitting either a supplement or a detailed crash investigation report pending the prognosis of Mr. Brenner.

Weight and Measurements:
The vehicle was not weighed. The vehicle was empty and being test driven to ensure roadworthiness following service at the time of the collision. Many components of the vehicle were removed/missing as a result of the crash and rescue operations including the fuel tank, battery compartment, hood, and upper cab of CMV.

Brakes:
The brakes appeared to have been recently serviced. The brake pads were full thickness. Air was supplied to the brake system by the tow truck directly to the air tanks. Brake measurements were obtained by marking the push-rods with the parking brakes off. The tow truck operator applied the brakes by pressing the treadle valve in the cab of the truck and measurements were obtained. The brakes functioned properly and there were no audible leaks from the brake air system. (See below photos)

D.        INSPECTION RESULTS: 
The CMV sustained catastrophic damage as a result of the crash. No pre-collision defects were observed. Post-collision defects include:
- U-Bolts shifted on leaf spring assembly on axle 1 left
- Axle 2 left outside tire flat (off rim)
- Axle 2 right outside tire flat (off rim)
- Left front headlight missing
- All lights were inoperative due to crash damage and the fact that the batteries were ejected as a result of the crash.
No enforcement action was taken because the commercial vehicle operator was not determined to be at fault.

Detailed Crash Investigation Supplement




Section I. - Narrative

On Monday, April 10, 2023, at approximately 1211 hours, the Prince George’s County Emergency Operations Center (EOC) notified the Maryland State Police College Park Barrack of a report of a multi-vehicle collision with two-vehicles overturned and entrapment. The collision was reported to be on the southbound side of Pennsylvania Avenue (MD 4), north of Ritchie Marlboro Road, Prince George’s County, Maryland. The Maryland State Police Forestville Barrack dispatched Trooper Christopher Reid #7458 to respond to investigate the collision. Due to the nature of the collision, a request was made for the Maryland State Police Crash Team to respond to assist with the investigation. I, Sergeant Kevin Zarzecki #6202, assigned to the Maryland State Police Crash Team, was notified at approximately 1251 hours and I arrived on the collision scene at approximately 1306 hours. Attached is my supplement report that documents my activities and investigative findings of the collision
 
Conclusion:

Due to the recovery of Devin Gardner, Roger Brenner, and James Lawson a full collision reconstruction will not be completed.

These collision events were determined to have been caused by Devin Lamont Gardner, the operator of the Ford E-350.

Upon approval, this report will be provided to Trooper Reid to utilize in his investigation.
